        <body>
            <p><add>?</add>evening with the sons of <persName>Mr Sassan</persName>, the rich Jewish
                banker of<lb/>
                <placeName>Bombay</placeName>. I stated there the same facts, I am herewith
                presenting<lb/> to the reader, and <del>the Chief Rabbi</del>
                <persName>Dr. Stern</persName> examining the Young <persName>Sassons</persName>,
                regar<lb/>ding the truth of my statements, they emphatically asserted, that<lb/>
                they could testify to his statement, as well as to the ingenuity of<lb/> my book.
                This assertion on the part of so highly respectable<lb/> witnesses refutes <del>not
                    only the alleged slander, but also</del> the statement<lb/> of the criticism,
                that I had compiled a book, without having wit-<lb/>nessed these distant
                regions.</p>
            <p>Thus the points raised by <del>Rev</del>
                <persName>Mr Gutheim</persName> against me, are open-<lb/>ly and frankly
                    <del>laid</del> refuted as willful <del>and malicious</del>
                misrepresen-<lb/>tations, and I have only to add, why <del>the Rev Rabbi of
                    New-OrË¶</del><lb/><del>leans at once has</del> he became so deadly hostile
                against me <add>after his first friendly recept.</add>, and<lb/> insisted upon the
                reconsideration <add>of the vote</add> passed by the Heb. Foreign Messers<lb/> in my
                favour.</p>
            <p><del>The Rev gentleman</del>
                <persName>Mr G.</persName>, namely, proposed to his congregation, to erect<lb/> a
                monument to the late <persName>Judah Touro</persName> in front of the new
                PortuË¶<lb/>guese Synagogue. According to the <hi rend="underline">Shulchan-Aruch,
                    Joreh-Deah</hi><lb/> I objected to his proposition, and published several
                articles against<lb/> his innovation. This step of mine excited the ire of the Rev.
                gentleË¶<lb/>man, that disregarding all justice and impartiality, and
                considering<lb/> only the merits or demerits of the case under consideration, he<lb/>
                <sic>recurrs</sic> to <del>slander and</del> calumny, in order to injure my cause
                and<lb/> reputation, and to weaken the objections, I had raised against<lb/> his
                favorite scheme.</p>
            <p>These, Mr Editor, are the plain and stubborn matters of fact. Let the<lb/> public now
                judge between me and <del>the Rev. Gentleman</del> him, and let them decide,<lb/>
                whether I have a right, to decry his <add>?</add> article as a <del>wilful</del><lb/>
                <del>and malicious slander!</del> totally unfounded</p>
            <p>Hoping, that you will insert into your valuable paper this article<lb/> of defense,
                as you have published the article from <placeName>New Orleans</placeName><lb/> I
                remain</p>
            <p>
                <add>?</add>
                <persName role="author">Benjamin II</persName>
            </p>
